Fixed cost models start similiarly to the other problems, but the cost is always fixed.  It could almost be compared to a constraint, because it doesn't change, and is necessary to make the problem successful. It is important because there are always business situations that have fixed cost problems.  It will be beneficial to have a model to help solve these problems, because it is happening in the real world. An example of this would be if you were selling pants and shirts, and the shirts were always at a fixed cost.  How much would you charge for the pants to optimize your profit? 

The best example for set-covering models would be a police station or fire station.  It's important that no parts of the city are left unprotected.  The set-covering model insures that there are no overlaps, but every part of the city would be covered.  This is highly important because you would not want a fire to happen between points A and B, and there not be a fire truck assigned to that street.  It is a matter of citizens safety.
